# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1905-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] The **$100,000 infield** was the infield of the Philadelphia Athletics in the early 1910s.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield consisted of first baseman Stuffy McInnis, second baseman Eddie Collins, shortstop Jack Barry and third baseman Frank "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] According to the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, the nickname reflects "the purported combined market value of the foursome", which is equivalent to about $2.44 million in 2024.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Baseball historian Bill James rated the 1914 edition of the $100,000 infield the greatest infield of all time, and also ranked the 1912 and 1913 editions in the top five all time.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield helped the Athletics win four American League championships in five years—1910, 1911, 1913 and 1914—and win the World Series in 1910, 1911 and 1913.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] The group was broken up after losing the 1914 World Series as a result of the financial pressures resulting from the emergence of the Federal League.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Two members—Collins and Baker—have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Collins was the first member of the $100,000 infield to join the Athletics.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He debuted on September 17, 1906, after playing college ball at Columbia University.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1906 and 1907, he played 20 games for the Athletics, mostly at shortstop.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1908, he took over as the Athletics' regular second baseman, replacing Danny Murphy, who moved to the outfield.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] During the $100,000 infield years from 1910 to 1914, he played 738 games, getting 922 hits in 2,677 at bats for a batting average of .344.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in runs in 1912, 1913 and 1914, stolen bases in 1910, singles in 1913 and times on base in 1914.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in the American League in batting average, on-base percentage, hits, stolen bases, singles and times on base every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] In addition, he finished in the top ten in American Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, winning the Most Valuable Player award in 1914.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Chicago White Sox after the 1914 season as Athletics' manager Connie Mack attempted to respond to the financial pressures brought on by the newly formed Federal League, breaking up the $100,000 infield.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He returned to Mack and the Athletics in 1927, finishing his career playing 12 games for the Athletics in their 1929 and 1930 World Championship seasons.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1939.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Barry was the next to join the Athletics, debuting on July 13, 1908, after playing for the College of the Holy Cross.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Barry played 686 games for the Athletics, getting 607 hits in 2,334 at bats for a batting average of .260.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the American League top ten in sacrifice hits every year from 1911 through 1914, and ranked fifth in the American League in runs batted in in 1913.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] But his primary contributions were on defense, where he had a strong arm, enormous range and sure hands, and was able to work out innovative plays with his good friend Collins, such as a defense against the double steal.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top 20 in Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, with his best showing a ninth-place finish in 1913.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Boston Red Sox in the middle of the 1915 season, where he moved to second base and played on the Red Sox' 1915 and 1916 World Championship teams.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He missed the Red Sox 1918 Championship season due to service in the U.S.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker also joined the Athletics in 1908, debuting on September 21.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He became the Athletics regular third baseman in 1909, and led the American League in triples that season.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Baker played 742 games for the Athletics, getting 929 hits in 2,864 at bats for a batting average of .324.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in home runs every year from 1911 through 1914, and led the league in runs batted in during 1912 and 1913.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in batting average, slugging percentage, on-base percentage and times on base every year from 1911 through 1914, and finished in the top ten in runs scored, hits, doubles, total bases, extra base hits and runs batted in every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top ten in the American League Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, finishing third in 1914, his highest showing.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was the hero of the 1911 World Series, hitting two home runs to help the Athletics win the series, which earned him the nickname "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker held out the 1915 season when manager and owner Connie Mack refused to increase his salary, and was sold to the New York Yankees in 1916 after American League president Ban Johnson intervened.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished his career as the third baseman for the Yankees pennant-winning teams in 1921 and 1922.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1955.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis was the final member of the $100,000 infield to join.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He started his career as an 18-year-old little-used backup infielder for the Athletics in 1909, and played a little more in 1910.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1909 and 1910, he played more games backing up Barry at shortstop than at any other position.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Before the 1911 season, Mack decided to make McInnis his regular first baseman, replacing the popular veteran Harry Davis, although McInnis did have to begin the season as the Athletics' shortstop when Barry became ill before taking over at first base.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Defensively as a first baseman, he was known for having exceptional reach.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, McInnis played 614 games for the Athletics, getting 715 hits in 2,228 at bats for a batting average of .321.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in singles in 1914, and finished in the top ten in batting average, hits, total bases, runs batted in and singles every year from 1912 through 1914.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] In both 1912 and 1913, he also finished in the top ten in slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He received Most Valuable Player votes every season from 1911 through 1914, finishing seventh in both 1913 and 1914.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis is the only member of the $100,000 infield to remain with the Athletics beyond 1915.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He was eventually traded to the Boston Red Sox in 1918 in exchange for Larry Gardner, Hick Cady and Tilly Walker, where he played on Boston's 1918 World Championship team.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] He also reteamed with Barry on the 1919 Boston Red Sox.
[src:1905-world-series/100-000-infield] Before finishing his career in 1927 he also played with the Cleveland Indians, Boston Braves, Pittsburgh Pirates and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1905-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1905-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1905-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1905-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The **1886 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fourth season.
[src:1905-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The team had a record of 75–44, finishing third in the National League, 12.5 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1905-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The **1887 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fifth season.
[src:1905-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 68–55, 10+1⁄2 games behind the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1905-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team amassed 415 stolen bases, the most for any team in the history of the National League.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] The **1905 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1905 season.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] The National League (NL) champion New York Giants defeated the American League (AL) champion Philadelphia Athletics, with the Giants winning 4 games to 1, now in a best-4-of-7 format.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Four of the five games featured duels between future Hall of Fame pitchers.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] The games were the second edition of the World Series after the initial meeting in 1903, since the 1904 season ended with no Series held, and the first to be officially sanctioned by the leagues and the National Baseball Commission.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] This was the first professional sports championship ever won by a New York City-based team.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Games 1 and 3 were played in Philadelphia; games 2, 4, 5 in New York.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Three of those, over a six-day span, were pitched and won by Christy Mathewson.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Before the Series began, the Athletics were already at a major disadvantage.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] For the Series, they were without the services of Rube Waddell, who was arguably their best pitcher that year.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] The reason for Waddell's absence was listed as a shoulder injury from some sort of 'wrestling match' with teammate Andy Coakley, though in years since some have speculated that Waddell was actually bribed or 'paid off' to fake the injury and thus not play in the Series.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Philadelphia manager Connie Mack, however, refused to believe this theory, finding it ridiculous.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] John McGraw, the Giants' manager, had previously referred to the Athletics as a "white elephant", which the club defiantly adopted as a symbolic mascot.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] At the conference at home plate before Game 1, A's team captain Lave Cross gave McGraw a wrapped package, which turned out to contain a toy white elephant.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] McGraw responded with a big grin, and the crowd laughed.[Philadelphia *Inquirer*, October 10, 2005, p.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] 10] McGraw and the Giants would have the last laugh, easily defeating the A's in the Series.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] The opening game was a pitchers' duel between Christy Mathewson and Eddie Plank.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Both got out of jams, shutting the opposing offense down.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] In the Giants' top of the fifth, Mathewson singled, but was forced by Roger Bresnahan, who stole second shortly afterwards.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] After George Browne popped out, Mike Donlin singled to left, scoring Bresnahan and advancing Donlin to second.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] After Dan McGann walked, Sam Mertes doubled, bringing home Donlin.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] In the Athletics' half of the sixth, Ossee Schreckengost doubled and advanced to third on a wild pitch, but did not score, and was the lone runner to reach third base against Mathewson in the entire series.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] The Giants added an insurance run in the ninth, when Billy Gilbert scored on Bresnahan's single.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] This was the first of Mathewson's three complete-game shutouts, a World Series record that may never be matched.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] The A's called on Chief Bender to turn the tables on the Giants.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] His opponent was 21-game winner "Iron Man" Joe McGinnity.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] The game was scoreless until the top of the third.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Ossee Schreckengost, leading off, reached on a Dan McGann's error.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Bender sacrificed, moving Schreckengost to second.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] After a groundout by Topsy Hartsel moved Schreckengost to third, Bris Lord singled to left and drove Ossee home with an unearned run.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] The slim margin held until the top of the eighth, when the A's scored multiple times.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] With one out, Schreckengost was once again the catalyst, singling to center.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] After Bender flied out to right field, Hartsel's double scored Schreckengost all the way from first (helped by an error from Bresnahan), and a single by Lord brought Hartsel home, making it 3–0 in favor of the A's with all three runs unearned.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Bender continued to cruise, got out of late-inning jams and ended up with a complete-game shutout that tied the series at one game each.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Christy Mathewson once again took the mound for the Giants in Game 3.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Opposing him this time was Andy Coakley, who hit the first batter he faced, Roger Bresnahan, with a pitch.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] A single to right by Mike Donlin moved Bresnahan to third with one out.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Dan McGann singled to right, bringing Bresnahan home.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] An error by Danny Murphy scored Donlin and put Sam Mertes on base.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Bill Dahlen walked, loading the bases with one out, but Art Devlin hit into a double play to end the rally.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] The Giants put the game away in the top of the fifth.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] George Browne singled and went to second on the throw to third base.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Donlin was walked intentionally, setting up a possible inning-ending double play, but things continued to crumble for Coakley and the A's.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] McGann reached on another error by Danny Murphy, reloading the bases and scoring a run.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Mertes singled, reloading the bases and driving in another run.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Bill Dahlen hit into a force play at second, scoring Donlin.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] After Dahlen stole second, Devlin singled, bringing home McGann and sending Dahlen to third.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Devlin then stole second and Dahlen stole home on a double steal, scoring the fifth and last run of the Giants' fifth.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] They scored two more runs in the top of the ninth, when McGann doubled home Browne and Donlin.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Mathewson pitched his second complete-game shutout, giving the Giants a 2–1 lead in the series.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] This was the first 9–0 World Series game—the next one occurred when the Cubs shut out the Tigers by that lopsided score in Game 1 in 1945, although Detroit ended up taking that series four games to three.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Eddie Plank returned for the A's against Joe McGinnity for the Giants in Game 4.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Both left men on base in scoring position early on, and kept the game scoreless until the bottom of the fourth, when Sam Mertes led off the inning by reaching on an error by Monte Cross.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] After Bill Dahlen flied to right Art Devlin grounded out, moving Mertes to second.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] With two outs, Billy Gilbert singled to left, bringing Mertes home for the only run of the game, McGinnity outdueling Plank 1–0 and giving the Giants a three-games-to-one lead.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] The Giants looked to wrap up the series behind the perennial Christy Mathewson, who faced Chief Bender this time.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] In the eighth, the Giants got an insurance run when Mathewson scored on George Browne's ground out after Roger Bresnahan's double had sent him to third with less than two out.
[src:1905-world-series/1905-world-series] Mathewson then took the mound for the top of the ninth and induced three ground outs, thereby completing arguably the single greatest performance by any player in World Series history with his third complete-game shutout of the series.
[src:1905-world-series/giants-season] The **1885 New York Giants season** was the franchise's third season.
[src:1905-world-series/giants-season] The team finished in second place, 2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
